# arvo-bits-contracts. Known gaps

Round 202604271346 lifted these items into arvo-bits-contracts as
part of the contract-crate split. Each has a deferred design-doc
follow-up that lands in the next DOC-phase round; until then the
SHAME entry silences the `undocumented-type` lint while still
recording the gap. Nothing on this list is a permanent escape; every
entry is a TODO for the next round.

## IBit

Private sealing trait gating `IBitPrim`. Lives inside the private
`mod sealed` and is impl'd in this crate on the bare signed
primitives `i8`, `i16`, `i32`, `i64`. The trait carries no methods;
its only purpose is to prevent consumers outside this crate from
adding new primitive widths to `IBitPrim`. The `undocumented-type`
lint cannot see the private-mod context and flags the bare
`pub(crate) trait` declaration. The next DOC-phase round adds an
explicit "Sealing traits" section to `DESIGN.md.tmpl`; until then
this SHAME entry records the gap.

## UBridge

Private sealing trait gating the `UBitContainer` blanket impl. Lives
inside `mod sealed`, is const-generic on `BITS`, and is blanket-impl'd
over `(Strategy, BITS)` pairs whose unsigned container implements
`BitPrim`. No methods; pure sealing token. Same lint blind-spot as
`IBit`: the lint flags the public-on-paper-but-private-in-practice
declaration. The next DOC-phase round documents the sealing trio
alongside the `BitPrim` family section; this SHAME entry temporarily
unblocks the SRC-phase commit gate per the lint's escape-hatch path.

## IBridge

Private sealing trait gating the `IBitContainer` blanket impl. Same
shape as `UBridge` but for the signed side: blanket-impl'd over
`(Strategy, BITS)` pairs whose signed container implements `IBitPrim`.
Separate from `UBridge` so a single `Strategy` can carry both a
U-bridge and an I-bridge at the same `BITS` without blanket-impl
collision. Same lint blind-spot, same DOC-phase follow-up, same
temporary SHAME entry until the doc lands. The doc CL for round
202604271346 will gain a sealing-traits subsection in pass 4 doc
clean-up or a follow-up DOC round.
